Package jpaul.DataStructs Description

Data structures for program analysis and not only. Here is a brief overview:

  • WorkSets (e.g., for fixed-point computations): WorkList, WorkSet, and WorkPriorityQueue.
  • Classes and interfaces for the Factory Design Pattern: Factory and its (many) children. Using the factory design pattern allows the programmer to switch from one data structure implementation to another with minimal effort. Of special importance are the set and map factories from SetFacts and MapFacts.
  • Binary and ternary relations: Relation, Relation3 and their children. These classes eliminate the need to manually handle maps to maps to sets, and provide other goodies too.
  • Copy-On-Write data structures: see SetFacts.cow and RelFacts.cow. Represent a middle point between mutation-based java.util data structures and purely functional datastructures (such as those from jutil).
  • Lots of useful static methods in DSUtil, many of them familiar to people with a functional programming background: map, filter etc.
  • Map with default values for unassigned keys: MapWithDefault. This may be useful if the programmer wants a default value that is not null.
  • The ever popular Pair: very often, we need to return more than one thing from a method. Returning an array of Objects loses type safety. Something like Pair<Integer,String> is far more informative.
